The message text is: `"Click + Claude Code or + Codex to start a session"`

### 2. Button Components

**File:** `/Users/alisha/Projects/entire-app/src/features/terminal/TerminalPanel.tsx` (Lines 112-126)

These are the actual button components in the terminal panel header. They appear when `session` is null:

```jsx
{!session ? (
  <>
    <button
      onClick={() => launchAgent("claude-code")}
      disabled={isLaunching}
      className="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md border border-border-subtle px-2.5 py-1 text-[11px] text-fg-subtle transition-colors hover:border-accent hover:text-accent-fg disabled:opacity-50"
    >
      + Claude Code
    </button>
    <button
      onClick={() => launchAgent("codex")}
      disabled={isLaunching}
      className="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md border border-border-subtle px-2.5 py-1 text-[11px] text-fg-subtle transition-colors hover:border-green hover:text-green disabled:opacity-50"
    >
      + Codex
    </button>
  </>
) : (
  // Active session content
)}
```

### 3. Session Creation Logic

**File:** `/Users/alisha/Projects/entire-app/src/features/terminal/TerminalPanel.tsx` (Lines 28-61)

The `launchAgent` function handles session creation:

```ts
const launchAgent = useCallback(
  async (agent: string) => {
    if (!tab.repoPath) {
      console.warn("No repo path set — cannot launch agent");
      return "";
    }
    if (isLaunching) return "";

    setIsLaunching(true);
    try {
      // Create a libghostty surface — it manages its own PTY internally.
      // Passing the agent name as the command tells ghostty to run that
      // CLI tool instead of the default shell.
      const surfaceId: string = await invoke("ghostty_create_surface", {
        workingDir: tab.repoPath,
        command: agent,
      });

      const newSession: TermSession = {
        id: surfaceId,
        agent,
        label: `${agent === "claude-code" ? "Claude Code" : "Codex"} — ${tab.branch}`,
      };
      onSessionChange(newSession);
      return surfaceId;
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("Failed to create ghostty surface:", err);
      return "";
    } finally {
      setIsLaunching(false);
    }
  },
  [tab.repoPath, tab.branch, isLaunching, onSessionChange]
);
```

### 4. Backend IPC Interface

**File:** `/Users/alisha/Projects/entire-app/src/lib/ipc.ts` (Lines 232-237)

The button clicks invoke the Tauri backend command:

```ts
export async function ghosttyCreateSurface(
  workingDir: string,
  command?: string
): Promise<string> {
  return invoke("ghostty_create_surface", { workingDir, command });
}
```

### 5. Session State Management

**File:** `/Users/alisha/Projects/entire-app/src/App.tsx` (Lines 54-80)

The App component manages per-branch session state:

```ts
const [sessionMap, setSessionMap] = useState<Map<string, TermSession>>(
  () => new Map()
);

const handleSessionChange = useCallback(
  (session: TermSession | null) => {
    setSessionMap((prev) => {
      const next = new Map(prev);
      if (session) {
        next.set(activeTabId, session);
      } else {
        next.delete(activeTabId);
      }
      return next;
    });
  },
  [activeTabId]
);
```

### 6. Agent Selection in Diff View

**File:** `/Users/alisha/Projects/entire-app/src/features/diff/ReviewBar.tsx` (Lines 27, 105-114)

The ReviewBar component also provides agent selection for sending prompts:

```jsx
const [agent, setAgent] = useState<"claude-code" | "codex">("claude-code");

<select
  value={agent}
  onChange={(e) =>
    setAgent(e.target.value as "claude-code" | "codex")
  }
  className="rounded border border-border-subtle bg-bg px-2 py-1 text-[11px] text-fg-muted outline-none focus:border-accent"
>
  <option value="claude-code">Claude Code</option>
  <option value="codex">Codex</option>
</select>
```

## Flow Summary

1. **GhosttyTerminal** displays the empty state message when `surfaceId` is null
2. **TerminalPanel** renders the "+ Claude Code" and "+ Codex" buttons when no session exists
3. Clicking either button calls `launchAgent()` with the agent name ("claude-code" or "codex")
4. `launchAgent()` invokes the Tauri backend command `ghostty_create_surface` with working directory and agent command
5. The backend returns a `surfaceId`, which creates a new `TermSession` object
6. Session state is managed via `sessionMap` in **App.tsx** per active tab
7. Once active, the session displays in the terminal panel header and **GhosttyTerminal** shows the native Metal overlay

